Entrepreneurs’ ability to attain finance is largely determined by their network position. Ideally, it combines close ties that transmit the trust needed to maintain a credit line with ties to more distant connections that provide access to more remote information and market opportunities (
 
  30
 ). Venture capitalists, who specialize in early-stage funding, need to be “rich in relationships even more than cash” (
 
  31
 ). They operate by bridging “structural holes” in networks between entrepreneurs and large institutional investors (
 
  32
 , 
 
  33
 ). Entrepreneurs seeking to construct innovative enterprises do so by harnessing the power of their networks to gather resources, discover opportunities, and gain legitimacy (
 
  27
 ).
